05439nam a22008655i 9780674060906DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979626927  a97806740609067 a10.4159/harvard.97806740609062doi  a(DE-B1597)178223  a(OCoLC)956656264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF3827.D4 7aLAW0990002bisacsh04a344.7304/191 aFoley, Elizabeth Price, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Law of Life and Death /cElizabeth Price Foley. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Statutory and Common Law Life -- t2. Constitutional Life -- t3. Cardiopulmonary Death -- t4. Brain Death -- t5. Constitutional Death -- t6. Not Dead Yet -- t7. Unbeing Dead Isn’t Being Alive -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAre you alive? What makes you so sure? Most people believe this question has a clear answer—that some law defines our status as living (or not) for all purposes. But they are dead wrong. In this pioneering study, Elizabeth Price Foley examines the many, and surprisingly ambiguous, legal definitions of what counts as human life and death.Foley reveals that “not being dead” is not necessarily the same as being alive, in the eyes of the law. People, pre-viable fetuses, and post-viable fetuses have different sets of legal rights, which explains the law's seemingly inconsistent approach to stem cell research, in vitro fertilization, frozen embryos, in utero embryos, contraception, abortion, homicide, and wrongful death.In a detailed analysis that is sure to be controversial, Foley shows how the need for more organ transplants and the need to conserve health care resources are exerting steady pressure to expand the legal definition of death. As a result, death is being declared faster than ever before. The ";right to die,"; Foley worries, may be morphing slowly into an obligation to die.Foley’s balanced, accessible chapters explore the most contentious legal issues of our time—including cryogenics, feticide, abortion, physician-assisted suicide, brain death, vegetative and minimally conscious states, informed consent, and advance directives—across constitutional, contract, tort, property, and criminal law. Ultimately, she suggests, the inconsistencies and ambiguities in U.S. laws governing life and death may be culturally, and perhaps even psychologically, necessary for an enormous and diverse country like ours.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeathxProof and certificationzUnited States. 0aEuthanasiaxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aLife and death, Power overxDecision making. 0aLife and death, Power overxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aRight to diexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aRight to lifezUnited States. 7aLAW / Science & Technology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET RECHTSWISSENSCHAFTEN 2011z9783110261264oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406090640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674060906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780